		<table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0">
			<tr>
			<td><table width="100%" border="0" cellspacing="0" cellpadding="0"><tr><td width="100%"><a href="viewtopic.php?p=90289&amp;sid=566779a067a04fe84c4bffa5e7157f2f#90289"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/icon_minipost.gif" width="12" height="9" alt="Post" title="Post" border="0" /></a><span class="postdetails">Posted: Sun Oct 17, 2004 7:26 am<span class="gen">&nbsp;</span>&nbsp; &nbsp;Post subject: Halo II</span></td>
				<td width="30%" valign="top" nowrap="nowrap" align="right"> <a href="posting.php?mode=quote&amp;p=90289&amp;sid=566779a067a04fe84c4bffa5e7157f2f"><img src="templates/eqluclin/images/lang_english/icon_quote.gif" alt="Reply with quote" title="Reply with quote" border="0" /></a>   </td></tr></table></td>
			</tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2"><hr /></td></tr>
			<tr><td colspan="2">
				<div class="postbody">
				Now, my copy is in French, so it's a bit hard to follow all of the nuances of the story because only the actual cinema scenes are subtitled, and the game makes very liberal use (far more than its predecessor) of in-game dialogue and interaction to tell the story. What I can follow is fantastic. The story has more action in the first five levels than the original Halo had in the entire game, and the story going with it has a lot more depth. The AI is fantastic, and on Legendary I can't even make a dent in them (yet). The soldiers finally hold their own and are more than speed bumps for the enemy this time. They can and will operate all of the vehicle types on their own now, including driving them. It feels and sounds like you are actually working as part of a military team instead of being the only real player on the field.
<br />

<br />
There's a dual story line going on, one with the dishonored high general of the Covenant legions and one with the Master Chief, a lot like in Legacy of Kain: Defiance. The Covenant are fleshed out wonderfully, giving us some background and culture that makes them much more interesting this time around instead of just a target on the firing range. More than that I won't divulge because there are some great suprises that shouldn't be spoiled. The game interface has changed a bit; they simply ditched "health" altogether and went with shield energy. All of the weapons have been rebalanced (perfectly imo) and a lot more were added on both sides. Dual weapon wielding is in, at least for small weapons, though you can't toss grenades while dual wielding. Dual needlers is just murder. There are more vehicles, and they have also been rebalanced and improved (and all are destructible now as well). If you are good, you can actually take over an enemy vehicle and throw its operator out (and they can do the same to you if you are reckless).
<br />

<br />
The graphics look like triple the poly count of the original. I've been through several parts that were simply breathtaking, and better than anything I've seen on a computer outside of pre-rendered games like Myst. Their level designers were going for the epic look and feel this time, and they nailed it dead on. I'm running the game in 480p and Halo 2 is taking full advantage of that extra resolution. The soundtrack is similary improved, using a lot of familiar themes from the original remixed and enhanced greatly, as well as plenty of new music. So far I like this soundtrack better than the first... the music is just more lively and atmospheric.
<br />

<br />
The best improvement, by far, is the level detail. The biggest failing of the original Halo was the repetitiveness of many of the levels. So far in the sequel I haven't seen anything repetitive at all. Gameplay types vary radically from vehicle warfare in cities to combat in and around space stations to stealthy assasination missions, all with the same military feel of the original. And I'm only a third (I'm guessing) of the way through it. Some of the levels have already been larger than anything in the original. They are much more interactive now and far larger in scope. Things you think are only in the background have a habit of interacting now (such as watching a ship nearby take out a skyscraper you happen to be standing beside, or seeing massive interstellar combat outside of a spaceship).
<br />

<br />
Co-op game now supports four players (and, I'll wager, 16 if enough Xboxes are hooked together). It also appears to be making use of the Xbox Live chat feature for voice chat with other team members. There is the usual smattering of online game types and deathmatch levels.
<br />

<br />
Bottom line: the story, levels, music, graphics, atmosphere, game play, and scope are all on par or above the original Half-Life, which was, until tonight, the best FPS I had ever played. Unless Halo 2 jumps the shark while I'm finishing it up it's definitely going to rate a 10/10 outstanding. It's an order of magnitude better than the original in every category. If you liked the original at all, you won't want to miss the sequel.<br />
				<span class="gensmall"></span><br />
				</div>
			</td></tr>
